<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="451" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,321]" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,150,176]" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species superficially resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Li &amp; Zhen, 2011" authorityName="Li &amp; Zhen" authorityYear="2011" box="[748,1282,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Gelechiidae" genus="Helcystogramma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="451" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavifuscum">
<emphasis box="[748,1077,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">Helcystogramma flavifuscum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Li, H. H. &amp; Zhen, H." box="[1086,1282,151,177]" pageId="16" pageNumber="451" pagination="1035 - 1087" refId="ref15326" refString="Li, H. H. &amp; Zhen, H. (2011) Review of the genus Helcystogramma Zeller (Lepidoptera: Gelechiidae: Dichomeridinae) from China. Journal of Natural History, 45 (17 - 18), 1035 - 1087. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222933.2011.552798" type="journal article" year="2011">Li &amp; Zhen, 2011</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, but it differs from the latter by having gradually broadened valva, the cornute lateral lobe of vinculum, whereas in the latter, the valva is narrowest medially, inflated distally.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="451" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,150,321]" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,259,285]" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin - 
<emphasis box="[856,917,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">albus</emphasis>
(= white) and 
<emphasis box="[1085,1197,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="451">macularis</emphasis>
(= spot), referring to the white spot at costal 2/ 
<quantity box="[438,480,295,321]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="16" pageNumber="451" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
the forewing.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
